ween the Wild and the Civilized: A Yiddish Travel Writer in Peru -- tPart V. Repre sen ta tions of Travel: Mapping and Remapping -- tIntroduction -- tContributors -- tChapter 12. The New Zionist Road Map: From Old Gravesites to New Settlements -- tChapter 13. Heritage Utterances in Jewish Destinations: Travelers, Texts, and Museum Visitor Books -- tChapter 14. Traveling, Seeing, and Painting: Amsterdam and the Creation of Jewish Art in the Work of Max Liebermann and Hermann Struck -- tChapter 15. Jerusalem Journeys: Wandering Women in Con temporary Israeli Cinema -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJourneys of dislocation and return, of discovery and conquest hold a prominent place in the imagination of many cultures. Wherever an individual or community may be located, it would seem, there is always the dream of being elsewhere. This has been especially true throughout the ages for Jews, for whom the promises and perils of travel have influenced both their own sense of self and their identity in the eyes of others.How does travel writing, as a genre, produce representations of the world of others, against which one's own self can be invented or explored? And what happens when Jewish authors in particular—whether by force or of their own free will, whether in reality or in the imagination—travel from one place to another? How has travel figured in the formation of Jewish identity, and what cultural and ideological work is performed by texts that document or figure specifically Jewish travel? Featuring essays on topics that range from Abraham as a traveler in biblical narrative to the guest book entries at contemporary Israeli museum and memorial sites; from the marvels medieval travelers claim to have encountered to eighteenth-century Jewish critiques of Orientalism; from the Wandering Jew of legend to one mid-twentieth-century Yiddish writer's accounts of his travels through Peru, Jews and Journeys explores what it is about travel writing that enables it to become one of the central mechanisms for exploring the realities and fictions of individual and collective identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJewish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aJewish literaturexThemes, motives. 0aJewish travelers. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJewsxTravel. 0aTravel in literature. 0aTravel writingxJewish authors. 0aTravelers' writingsxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aJewish Studies.  aLiterature.  aReligion.1 aBartal, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashkin, Orit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashkin, Orit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrenkel, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKugelmass, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Joshua, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLimor, Ora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoy, Chaim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoemer, Nils, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRokem, Galit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubiés, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalah, Asher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShein, Iris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela